#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""
Strict two-pass wrapper for yt-dlp that guarantees all *required* subtitles
have been downloaded successfully before downloading media.

By default, yt2pass only ever considers **human-made** subtitles.  
Automatically generated captions / translations are *ignored* unless you pass
the `--auto` flag.

Pass 1 (subtitles only):
    - Probes the video metadata once.
    - Determines which of the requested subtitle languages are actually available.
    - Runs yt-dlp with a "subs-first" config (slow, patient).
    - Repeats with cooldowns until all required .srt files exist locally.

    Required vs best-effort behavior:

      • Without --auto:
          - Only human-made subtitles are considered.
          - For each requested language base in --langs, any human-made tracks
            that exist are treated as required.
          - If a requested language only exists as auto-captions/auto-translation,
            it is treated as “not available” and is not fetched.

      • With --auto:
          - Human-made subtitles are still treated as required.
          - The original-language track (if detectable) is also treated as required
            even when it is only available as auto-captions.
          - Additional auto-generated / auto-translated subtitles (i.e., languages
            that exist *only* as auto) are treated as best-effort: yt2pass retries
            them, but persistent HTTP 429s will cause those languages to be skipped
            with a warning so the download can still succeed.

      • With --auto and --strict:
          - *All* requested subtitle languages (including auto-generated /
            auto-translated ones) are treated as required.
          - On repeated HTTP 429s, yt2pass uses a long (and increasing) backoff
            between attempts (on the order of many minutes) and fails hard if any
            requested language is still missing after max-tries.

Pass 2 (media only):
    - Runs yt-dlp with a media-only set of flags (no subtitle fetching).
    - Embeds the already-downloaded .srt files into the final MKV.

This program depends on yt-dlp, so it also checks that yt-dlp is installed and up to date.

Written by Emmy Killett

INSTALL PROCESS USING PIPX:

# 0) Make sure ~/.local/bin is first on PATH for this session and future logins
export PATH="$HOME/.local/bin:$PATH"
grep -q 'export PATH="$HOME/.local/bin:$PATH"' ~/.profile || \
  echo 'export PATH="$HOME/.local/bin:$PATH"' >> ~/.profile

# 1) Install pipx
sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install -y pipx
pipx ensurepath   # ok to ignore the “restart shell” hint for now

# 2) Install yt-dlp (nightly / pre-release) via pipx and FORCE re-link the shim
pipx install --force --pip-args="--pre" yt-dlp

# 3) Add the impersonation dependency inside THAT venv
pipx runpip yt-dlp install --upgrade "curl_cffi>=0.6.0"
pipx runpip yt-dlp install -U "yt-dlp[default]"

# 4) (Recommended) Install a JS runtime so yt-dlp can solve YouTube’s JS challenges
sudo apt-get install -y nodejs

# 5) Verify the right binary is being used and the shim points to the venv
command -v yt-dlp
readlink -f ~/.local/bin/yt-dlp
~/.local/share/pipx/venvs/yt-dlp/bin/yt-dlp -v --ignore-config --version

# You should see in the verbose header:
#   Optional libraries: ... curl_cffi ...
#   JS runtimes: node

TO UPGRADE:
pipx upgrade --pip-args="--pre" yt-dlp

TO INSTALL aria2c (optional downloader):
sudo apt-get update
sudo apt-get install -y aria2
"""

